solutions.content:
# Intuition
Since the n is very small we could try all the permutations. 

# Approach
To solve this problem, we will use a recursive backtracking algorithm. The main idea behind backtracking is to explore all possible combinations by trying out different choices and then undoing those choices if they lead to invalid solutions. We will start with the main array `nums` and swap and permutate it untill we reach our base case.

1. Base Case:
We need to identify the base case of the recursion, i.e., when to stop generating permutations. In our case, the base case will be when the i which is the index of the array reaches the end of the array which is `nums.size()`.

2. Recursive Function:
We will define a recursive function, let's call it `recur`, which will be responsible for generating the permutations. This function will take the following parameters:
   - `nums`: The original array which we will use to generate all the permutations.
   - `i`: index of the element at which it is currently present.

3. Initialization:
We will start by calling the recursive `recur` function with `nums` and `i` the 0th index at which we are starting.

4. Backtracking Algorithm:
Inside the `recur` function, we will do the following steps:
   a. Check the base case: If the length of `i` equals the length of `nums`, add it to the array of valid permutations.
   b. Iterate through the `nums` array:
      i. Swap the i<sup>th</sup> element with the j<sup>th</sup> element.
      ii. Call for the function recursively for the next index which is i + 1.
      iii. Backtrack by undoing what we did with swaping back that i<sup>th</sup> element with the j<sup>th</sup> 

Conclusion:
By implementing the above approach, we can efficiently generate all possible permutations of the given array `nums`. The backtracking algorithm ensures that we explore all possible combinations while efficiently avoiding invalid solutions.

