# Intuition of this Problem :
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/14fe9f74-0ba3-42db-ab6c-74e0554f21d2_1683001886.1161199.png)

*The problem of generating all permutations of a given array can be solved using a recursive backtracking algorithm. The basic idea is to swap each element of the array with every other element in the array, and then recursively generate all permutations of the remaining elements. Once we have generated all permutations of the remaining elements, we swap the original elements back to restore the original order of the array.*

<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Code :
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    // Recursive helper function to generate permutations
    void helper(int l, int r, vector<int>& nums, vector<vector<int>>& ans) {
        // Base case: when left and right pointers are equal,
        // we have generated a permutation and add it to the answer.
        if (l == r) {
            ans.push_back(nums);
            return;
        }
        // Recursive case: for each index i in the range [l, r],
        // swap nums[l] with nums[i], generate permutations of the rest
        // of the array, and then swap back to restore original order.
        else {
            for (int i = l; i <= r; i++) {
                swap(nums[l], nums[i]); // Swap nums[l] with nums[i]
                helper(l+1, r, nums, ans); // Recursively generate permutations for remaining indices
                swap(nums[l], nums[i]); // Swap back to restore original order
            }
        }
    }
    // Main function to generate permutations
    vector<vector<int>> permute(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        helper(0, nums.size()-1, nums, ans); // Generate permutations starting from index 0 to n-1
        return ans;
    }
};

```

# Time Complexity and Space Complexity:
- **Time Complexity :** **O(n * n!)**, where n! is the number of permutations of an n-element array.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- **Space Complexity :** **O(n * n!)**, In the recursive helper function, we are using the call stack to store the state of each recursive call. The maximum depth of the call stack is n, which corresponds to the length of the input array.
